comment.body:
> a few questions, more to come
> 
> 1. From a quick glimpse, this works by copying the atom container, and then modifying the matches (which I believe is more intuitive). RDKIT on the other hand does things differently, it matches the atoms first, and then only copies those (unchanged) atoms over that in the same component as atoms in the transformation. While this leads to some quirks in rdkit, it makes more generic removal operations quite easy (`[#6:1]-[B:2](*)*>>[#6:1]H`). Would that be supported?

Actually you can also modify in place using the ``apply(mol)`` utility. This runs the equivalent of Daylight's "dt_xapply" over the molecule. I would not worry about the copies and this implementation should be quite efficient. Feel free to run some benchmarks and compare (some example attached below).

> 2. does the current implementation also automatically reaction-map the atoms?

No but that is possible, it currently outputs molecules rather than reactions.

# [#6:1]-[B:2](*)*>>[#6:1][H]

It's not quite clear what you want this example to do, do you intend the '*' to flood fill, as written you would break bonds on something like: CB(OC)OC and leave two disconnected ``CH3`` left over. Either way here is some code that runs the transform over ChEMBL 31 and reports how long it took.

```java
public class CdkSmirksRun {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws FileNotFoundException {
        SmilesParser smipar = new SmilesParser(SilentChemObjectBuilder.getInstance());
        SmilesGenerator smigen = new SmilesGenerator(SmiFlavor.Default);

        Transform transform = new Transform();
        if (!Smirks.parse(transform, "[#6:1]-[B:2](*)*>>[#6:1][H]")) {
            System.err.println("Error: " + transform.message());
            return;
        }

        int count = 0;
        long t0 = System.nanoTime();
        try (BufferedReader brdr = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("/data/chembl_31.smi"));
             BufferedWriter bwtr = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("/tmp/transform.out"))) {
            String line;
            while ((line = brdr.readLine()) != null) {
                try {
                    IAtomContainer mol = smipar.parseSmiles(line);
                    if (transform.apply(mol)) {
                        bwtr.write(smigen.create(mol) + " input=" + line + "\n");
                    }
                } catch (Exception ex) {
                    System.err.println("Warning: " + ex.getMessage());
                }
                if ((++count % 10000) == 0) {
                    System.err.printf("\r%,d (%,.0f per second)...", count, count/((System.nanoTime()-t0)/1e9));
                }
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        System.err.printf("Total time: %.3f s", (System.nanoTime()-t0)/1e9);
    }
}
```

